## Handling Different Delimiters



Some files use different separators (semicolon, tab, etc.):
# Create file with semicolon separator

data = "Name;Age;City\nAlice;25;NYC\nBob;30;LA"

with open('data_semicolon.csv', 'w') as f:

    f.write(data)



# Read with custom delimiter

df = pd.read_csv('data_semicolon.csv', sep=';')

print(df)
# Tab-separated values

df = pd.read_csv('data.tsv', sep='\t')
---



## Handling Files Without Headers
# Create CSV without header row

data = "Alice,25,New York\nBob,30,Paris"

with open('no_header.csv', 'w') as f:

    f.write(data)



# Read and specify column names

df = pd.read_csv('no_header.csv', 

                 header=None,

                 names=['Name', 'Age', 'City'])

print(df)
---



## Skipping Rows
# Skip first N rows

df = pd.read_csv('data.csv', skiprows=2)
# Skip specific rows

df = pd.read_csv('data.csv', skiprows=[0, 2, 3])
---



## Selecting Specific Columns
# Read only certain columns

df = pd.read_csv('employees.csv', usecols=['Name', 'Salary'])

print(df)
---



## Handling Missing Data



CSV files often have missing values:
# Create CSV with missing values

data = """Name,Age,Salary

Alice,25,50000

Bob,,60000

Charlie,35,

Diana,28,55000"""



with open('missing_data.csv', 'w') as f:

    f.write(data)



# Read CSV - missing values become NaN

df = pd.read_csv('missing_data.csv')

print(df)
# Check for missing values

print(df.isnull())
# Count missing values per column

print(df.isnull().sum())
# Drop rows with missing values

df_clean = df.dropna()

print(df_clean)
# Fill missing values

df_filled = df.fillna(0)

print(df_filled)
---



## Specifying Data Types
# Specify data types for columns

df = pd.read_csv('employees.csv', 

                 dtype={'Name': str, 'Age': int, 'Salary': float})

print(df.dtypes)
